In the 1920s and 1930s, the Italian fascists began using the Roman salute as a greeting to emphasize the connection of the renewed Italy with the traditions of Ancient Rome. Following their example, the German Nazis adopted the Nazi salute, which visually resembles a Roman salute. The similarity of the gestures has led to confusion, especially since the outbreak of World War II. From 1939 until the attack on Pearl Harbor, opponents of U.S. involvement in the war tried not to use the Bellamy salute, so that they would not be considered supporters of the Nazis. For example, the famous American pilot Charles Lindbergh and his supporters were forced to justify themselves and prove that Lindbergh did not support Hitler and that the photographs showed not a Nazi greeting, but a Bellamy salute. Biographer Scott Berg argues that the scandalous photos were taken without capturing the U.S. flag, which makes the Bellamy salute indistinguishable from the Nazi salute.

On December 22, 1942, Congress passed amendments to the United States Flag Code and the oath to the flag was pronounced with the right hand palm over the heart.

Also, roman salute is a misnomer, it was never a thing in ancient Rome. The idea originates mainly from the painting "Le Serment des Horaces", where the characters from the painting are swearing and oath by raising their hands, and from ancient statues depicting emperors and important romans (like the famous statue of Augustus) doing an oratorial sign addressing the people, with their hand partially raised (erroneously attributed as "the roman salute", but it looks nothing like it, the arm is not fully extended, the hand is in different position and the purpose of it isn't to salute but to address an audience of people). It's basically a pop history myth, made popular by movies and tv shows where you have legionaries doing it, when it's actually bs.
 The roman salute is a fascist and nazi thing, not a roman thing at all.

I am not surprised by the fact that many Americans do not know their history. Many people, even in my country Greece, believe that this greeting comes from either ancient Greece or ancient Rome, but this is not written anywhere. This greeting historically first appeared in the 19th century in the United States of America. The creator of the greeting was Francis Julius Bellamy. It seems that he wanted to sell some flags through the company he worked for, to American schools. So on 12/10/1892 he found the opportunity to create the greeting. The greeting means the hand first to the heart and then extended towards the American flag. There are also photographic documents that show children in American schools during the term of President Franklin Delano Roosevelt greeting with Bellamy's greeting. Unfortunately, this salute was abolished in 1942 because it was considered a Nazi symbol. Now the question is: how did the Bellamy salute get appropriated by the fascists and the Nazis? Well, after the first world war, Gabriele D'Annunzio (an Italian Nazi poet and military man) stole the salute and in order not to say that the salute was American, he lied that it came from ancient Rome. That's what happened.

For all non-thinking individuals: The Bellamy salute is a palm-out salute created by James B. Upham as the gesture that was to accompany the Pledge of Allegiance of the United States of America, whose text had been written by Francis Bellamy. It was also known as the "flag salute" during the period when it was used with the Pledge of Allegiance. Bellamy promoted the salute and it came to be associated with his name. Both the Pledge and its salute originated in 1892. Later, during the 1920s and 1930s, Italian fascists and Nazi Germans adopted a salute which was very similar, attributed to the so-called Roman salute, a gesture is wrongly attributed to having been used in ancient Rome.

TLDR: Watching billionaires embrace authoritarian rhetoric isn‚Äôt surprising.  It‚Äôs consistent with capitalism‚Äôs DNA, self-interest. Think of our Constitutional Republic vs an unregulated me-first version of capitalism as opposing forces. Democracy distributes power and Capitalism concentrates it.  As wealth becomes more concentrated, it protects itself by buying political power. 

Concentrated wealth then uses the us-versus-them culture-war industry makes authoritarianism feel normal. Right now we‚Äôre seeing tech billionaires framing themselves as warrior-priests and philosopher-kings who should be able to rule without the consent of the governed.  

The pattern is clear:

Buy media platforms
Fund thinks tanks
Control information flow
Drive public opinion
Shape favorable economic policy
Destabilize democratic institutions 
Neutralize ‚Äúwe the people‚Äù

This is not a conspiracy - it‚Äôs money protecting money. 

Again, when wealth inequality reaches extreme levels, protecting that wealth becomes more valuable than maintaining our constitutional republic. The ultra-wealthy start viewing democracy as a threat to their financial position. This is nothing new. They have always done this. Except now, they‚Äôve learned to use patriotic overtones while pushing unpatriotic policies. They talk about freedom while building systems of control. Classic doublespeak but with incredible branding. 

The real question isn‚Äôt whether billionaires will support authoritarian movements - history shows they do. The question is whether democratic institutions, powered by ‚Äúwe the people‚Äù are strong enough to resist capital‚Äôs gravitational pull. 

This isn‚Äôt about individuals. You‚Äôre not the enemy. This is about systems and incentives. When we fixate on personalities, we ignore the hidden forces at work.
